import SourceChainFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/SourceChainFlow.astro";
---

<ChapterShell chapterId="02" locale="en">
  <div slot="thesis">
    <p>
      When a Tool call both changes the world and emits a huge payload, how do you keep evidence of
      what happened without crushing the next inference in the same Turn? The answer is not blunt
      truncation — separate fact, raw bytes, evidence, and context, then hold:
      <strong>Prune the context, never prune the evidence.</strong>
    </p>
  </div>

  <Section
    id="scene"
    label="§02 · Scene"
    title="Start from a gigantic test log"
    lede="The same Tool Result triggers four needs at once — one JSON blob cannot carry all of them."
  >
    <p>
      Suppose the user asks Maka to fix a failing test. The model calls Bash; the test process dumps
      80,000 lines. That result must simultaneously:
    </p>
    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>Show the model the critical errors so it can choose the next step;</li>
      <li>Leave replayable Bash call/result facts in the Runtime;</li>
      <li>Keep full raw logs recoverable later — a one-line summary is not enough;</li>
      <li>Keep the next model call in the same Turn from carrying all 80,000 lines again.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Stuffing forever into the prompt wrecks the budget; deleting destroys auditability; letting the
      model claim “I verified” mixes observation with judgment. The real question is not “how many
      characters to truncate,” but: what must be durable, what can be rebuilt, and what should live
      only briefly in the model’s working set?
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="keystone"
    label="§02 · Keystone"
    title="Turn-level evidence pipeline"
    lede="Scene-local metaphor; the fixed system is NewsLiquid tokens, hand keystones, and motion discipline."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      prototype
      caption="Fig. 1 · A Tool Result splits into four representations; only path 05 (Provider messages) is the active-prune rewrite surface — 01–04 are not “deletable evidence.”"
      alt="Pipeline from Tool execution to Runtime Event, Artifact, Turn Evidence, then Provider messages; 01–04 persist as evidence; 05 may be pruned; invariant: Prune the context, never prune the evidence."
    >
      <EvidencePipelineKeystone />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <p class="figure-note">
      Invariant: <strong>Prune the context, never prune the evidence.</strong>
      Active prune rewrites only the terminal provider-visible projection — it is not a retention
      policy.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="four"
    label="§02 · Four representations"
    title="One Tool Result, four representations"
    lede="Evidence compression may change how the model later sees a fact — not whether the fact occurred."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 2 · Same result as Durable Fact / Raw Artifact / Turn Evidence / Ephemeral Working Context — distinct authority and lifecycle."
      alt="Four columns: Runtime Fact, Artifact, Turn Evidence, Working context."
    >
      <FourRepsFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Four representations: question, authority, lifecycle" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Representation</th>
            <th scope="col">Question answered</th>
            <th scope="col">Authority</th>
            <th scope="col">Lifecycle</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Canonical Runtime Fact</td>
            <td>What was called and returned</td>
            <td>Interaction semantics</td>
            <td>Durable ledger</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Raw Artifact</td>
            <td>Where is the full payload; can it be verified</td>
            <td>Raw bytes</td>
            <td>Independent store + hash</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Turn Evidence</td>
            <td>Which public observations remain worth consuming</td>
            <td>Source-bearing derived</td>
            <td>Bounded / rebuildable</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Model Working Context</td>
            <td>Minimum the next step must see</td>
            <td>Ephemeral projection</td>
            <td>Recomputed per request</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Four-layer pipeline">Tool execution
  → RuntimeEvent(function_call / function_response)
  → Artifact(raw payload)
  → TurnEvidence(source-bearing bounded projection)
  → Provider Messages(current working set)</pre>

    <p>
      These are not simple copies: RuntimeEvent holds semantics; Artifact holds large payloads;
      Evidence holds source, summary, and integrity; Provider Messages serve the current decision and
      may be trimmed, compacted, or reordered.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="tool-runtime"
    label="§02 · ToolRuntime"
    title="ToolRuntime is the side-effect boundary"
    lede="Not a thin wrapper around tool.impl — guard and permission failures still leave a pairable tool result."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 3 · ToolRuntime in six beats: persist call → guards → permission → execute → normalize tool_result → async artifact."
      alt="Six-step swimlane: Persist call, Guards, Permission, Execute, tool_result, async Artifact; footnotes on synthetic error results and pairing."
    >
      <ToolRuntimeSwimlane />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>Persist <code>tool_call</code> and emit <code>tool_start</code>;</li>
      <li>Guards: loop gate, step availability, in-Turn concurrency caps;</li>
      <li>Permission evaluate: allow / block / prompt (wait for the user when needed);</li>
      <li>Run real <code>impl</code>: propagate abort; allow output deltas;</li>
      <li>Normalize and persist <code>tool_result</code> (paired to the call by <code>toolCallId</code>);</li>
      <li>Best-effort async artifact derive — a recorder failure must not mutate the result.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Unloaded tools, denied permission, repeated identical failures, sub-agent concurrency
      overflow — these paths <strong>do not vanish silently</strong>. ToolRuntime writes a synthetic
      error tool result so both the model and the RuntimeEvent ledger know the call was refused and
      why. A function call without a result breaks history pairing and leaves Evidence unable to tell
      “never executed” from “explicitly refused at the boundary.”
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="layers"
    label="§02 · Layers"
    title="output / result / artifact are not the same thing"
    lede="Prune never “deletes the tool output” — separate streaming progress, structured results, and independent payloads."
  >
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        <strong>output delta</strong> — in-flight streaming progress; may feed the UI; not the
        authoritative next-step fact.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>tool result</strong> — structured outcome the model acts on next; enters the ledger
        and pairing.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>artifact</strong> — file, diff, or large payload worth independent storage and
        display; own lifecycle and checksum.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Current derivation is conservative: Write may derive a file, Edit a diff, Bash only explicit
      stdout redirects. Recorder failures emit warnings only; slow recorders do not block returning
      the result to the model. Ordinary ArtifactRecords today may not fully carry
      <code>toolCallId</code> / RuntimeEvent refs — Target TurnEvidence must add that source linkage
      rather than pretend it already exists.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="turn"
    label="§02 · Boundary"
    title="Why Turn is the natural Evidence boundary"
    lede="Steps are too fine; Sessions are too wide; Turn is the operable midpoint."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 4 · Source chain: RuntimeEvent → Artifact → Turn Evidence → later consumers; raw remains fetchable by ref."
      alt="Four steps: RuntimeEvent, Artifact ref, Turn Evidence, Later consumer."
    >
      <SourceChainFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <p>
      Model/tool events in this round share a <code>turnId</code>; tool call/result, permission, and
      artifacts can belong to the same round; a Turn terminal fact marks completed / failed /
      aborted. The next Turn can treat prior Evidence as bounded engineering memory without expanding
      every raw dump.
    </p>
    <p>Turn Evidence should be able to answer:</p>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Questions Evidence must answer">What was this Turn trying to accomplish?
Which tools did it actually call?
What public results were observed?
Which artifacts were produced or mutated?
Which outputs were truncated, archived, or omitted?
Which canonical facts and raw payloads do the summaries point back to?</pre>
    <p>
      It must <strong>not</strong> answer “an official verifier certainly passed,” nor replace Runtime
      terminal status. Evidence describes sourced observations; conclusions and authoritative outcomes
      live elsewhere (see §05).
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="active"
    label="§02 · Active prune"
    title="Active prune: same-Turn request shaping"
    lede="Archive before omission. Fail open. A provider request-shaping policy — not a retention policy."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 5 · Active prune protocol: Hash → Archive OK? → placeholder / keep original → next provider step; ledger dashed bypass never moves."
      alt="Decision diamond: Archive OK yields source-bearing placeholder, else keep original fail open; RuntimeEvent/Session ledger dashed as unrewritten."
    >
      <ActivePruneFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <p>
      Stale pruning handles prior-history replay; Active Tool Result Prune answers the sharper
      question: Step 1 just produced a huge tool result — must Step 2 resend it verbatim? It runs in
      the AI SDK <code>prepareStep</code> hook — between the end of one provider step and assembly of
      the next — and only touches eligible large results from completed steps in the current Turn.
    </p>

    <p>Protocol (numbered on the page):</p>
    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>
        Eligible: completed steps in the current Turn; over the estimated-token threshold (Desktop
        default ~2048 — a <strong>policy knob, not a protocol constant</strong>);
      </li>
      <li>Stable-serialize → compute <code>bodySha256</code> / bytes / estimate;</li>
      <li>Host archive writer must return a non-empty <code>artifactId</code>;</li>
      <li>Only then build the placeholder;</li>
      <li>Replace only in this <code>prepareStep</code> messages view;</li>
      <li>Ledger / Session persisted results stay <strong>untouched</strong>.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>Placeholder fields (<code>reason</code> enum stays English code in both locales):</p>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Active prune placeholder fields">artifactId, turnId, toolCallId, toolName,
bodySha256, originalEstimatedTokens, originalBytes,
rewriteVersion,
reason = active_current_turn_tool_result_pruned_before_next_step</pre>

    <p>
      Active prune does <strong>not</strong>: delete the ledger; rewrite Session-persisted results;
      summarize business meaning; claim placeholder == full evidence; omit on archive failure to save
      tokens; handle every old historical result.
    </p>

    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">Evolution aside · mechanism</p>
      <p>
        Mechanism intro:
        <a href={`${localePath("en", "history/pr/316")}`}>maka:pr:316</a>
        (Add active tool result pruning). Archive-before-placeholder discipline:
        <a href={`${localePath("en", "history/pr/319")}`}>maka:pr:319</a>
        (require archived active tool pruning). Default-on:
        <a href={`${localePath("en", "history/pr/498")}`}>maka:pr:498</a>. Docs land (secondary):
        <a href={`${localePath("en", "history/pr/769")}`}>maka:pr:769</a>.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="stale"
    label="§02 · Stale prune"
    title="Stale prune: a different policy for prior history"
    lede="Two policies, two pressures — collapsing them swaps “current Turn” for “replay history.”"
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 6 · Active (same-Turn prepareStep) vs Stale (prior-history materialization) — different targets, timing, and misuse risks."
      alt="Two columns: Active same Turn prepareStep; Stale prior history replay materialization."
    >
      <ActiveVsStaleFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Active vs Stale contrast" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col"></th>
            <th scope="col">Active</th>
            <th scope="col">Stale</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">When</th>
            <td>Same Turn, between steps (<code>prepareStep</code>)</td>
            <td>Prior-history materialization</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Target</th>
            <td>Just-produced large results</td>
            <td>Old oversized tool results in replay</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Risk if confused</th>
            <td>Rewrite “history” mid-Turn incorrectly</td>
            <td>Miss current-Turn context pressure</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>
      The active path does not rewrite same-named large results inside history replay; prior history
      has its own stale strategy. Default-on evolution:
      <a href={`${localePath("en", "history/pr/621")}`}>maka:pr:621</a> (aside — not a full product
      history).
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="fail"
    label="§02 · Fail-open"
    title="Fail-open and the failure matrix"
    lede="What happens when archive fails? Keep the full provider message. Correctness &gt; savings."
  >
    <p>
      Any of these keep the original result: archive throws / returns nothing / empty
      <code>artifactId</code>; unsupported payload shape; under threshold; tool call not in current
      completed steps. Legal placeholders are recognized on later prepare passes and are not
      re-archived; identical bodies reuse a stable artifact ID.
    </p>

    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Failure matrix" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table proto-table--fail">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Failure</th>
            <th scope="col">Current behavior</th>
            <th scope="col">Architectural meaning</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Permission denied</td>
            <td>Synthetic error tool result</td>
            <td>Call ends explicitly; no real side effect</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Tool throws</td>
            <td>Normalized error + telemetry</td>
            <td>Failure is a pairable fact, not a lost event</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Artifact derive fails</td>
            <td>Warning; result continues</td>
            <td>Missing helper artifact must not change outcome</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Active archive fails</td>
            <td>Keep full provider message</td>
            <td>Correctness over token savings</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Placeholder corrupt on hydrate</td>
            <td>Explicit failure</td>
            <td>Never fake damaged bytes as raw evidence</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Process stops mid-tool</td>
            <td>Partial / operational recovery</td>
            <td>Never synthesize success evidence</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Official verifier is private</td>
            <td>Exclude from model projection</td>
            <td>authority ≠ visibility</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="compact-current"
    label="§02 · Current compact"
    title="Current: Heavy-task compact evidence"
    lede="Mature, but task/attempt-scoped — not yet universal Runtime TurnEvidence."
  >
    <p>
      <code>heavy-task-evidence</code> already implements compact evidence rules: Bash records
      command / cwd / exit / timeout with bounded stdout/stderr; Read/Grep/Glob record path, query,
      and bounded observation; Write/Edit record size, path, and mutation summary only (no body / raw
      diff); Artifact evidence stores metadata only; non-public or suspected official-verifier
      content is omitted; prompts project only the recent ~8 envelopes; truncation records original /
      visible / omitted bytes and ref kind.
    </p>
    <blockquote class="pull">
      Compact Evidence answers “which recent public observations help the next round avoid repeat
      work,” not “this is enough to prove an official pass.”
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      Envelope durable identity is still primarily <code>taskRunId</code> plus optional
      <code>attemptId</code>; <code>turnId</code> / <code>sessionId</code> / <code>toolCallId</code>
      live in <code>source</code>. That fits Headless heavy-task, but is not universal TurnEvidence
      across Runtime surfaces.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="target-envelope"
    label="§02 · Target"
    title="Target: TurnEvidence envelope"
    lede="visibility × authority; source-bearing; projection is not a proof chain. Not claimed as fully landed."
  >
    <p>
      Universal TurnEvidence should be a source-bearing derived record above RuntimeEvent and
      Artifact — durable enough for efficient replay/export, yet re-verifiable from canonical facts
      and raw artifacts; never a second source of truth. Conceptual fields include Turn identity,
      <code>source</code> refs, <code>visibility</code> (model_visible / internal / restricted),
      <code>authority</code> (observation / advisory / authoritative), bounded summary, and
      <code>integrity</code> (hash / bytes / truncation).
    </p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Source-bearing</strong> — summaries must point back to RuntimeEvents, archive
        artifacts (with hash), or accepted checks; otherwise they are low-authority observations.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Visibility ≠ authority</strong> — public and model-visible may still be mere
        observation; an official verifier may be authoritative yet must not leak into the prompt.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Projection, not proof chain</strong> — derived inside the Runtime; the model may
        consume it, but does not author authority.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div class="stub">
      <p class="stub__tag">Current vs Target</p>
      <p>
        Current building blocks: ToolRuntime + RuntimeEvent + ArtifactStore + active prune +
        heavy-task compact evidence. Target: unified Turn-scoped envelope and complete source
        linkage. Default token thresholds are policy knobs, not protocol constants. Teaching centers
        the invariants; Target is not disguised as shipped.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="invariants"
    label="§02 · Invariants"
    title="Seven invariants that must never break"
    lede="Do not sacrifice these while chasing tokens. You should be able to recite them."
  >
    <ol class="plain-list numbered invariants">
      <li>
        <strong>Prune projection, never ledger</strong> — rewrite only the provider-visible
        projection; never replace a ledger function response with a placeholder.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Archive before omission</strong> — only after the full raw payload is persisted and a
        verifiable artifact ref exists may a placeholder omit the large body.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Failure keeps evidence</strong> — archive / compaction / artifact failures must not
        forge a recoverable ref; active prune keeps the original.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Evidence must name its source</strong> — untraceable summaries are low-authority
        observations only.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Tool call/result pairing remains valid</strong> — deny, throw, cancel, and guard
        failure still produce matching results; prune/replay must not break the pair.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Authority never leaks into visibility</strong> — official/private evidence does not
        enter the prompt because it is authoritative; public summaries do not become official proof
        because they are visible.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Rewrites are idempotent and diagnosable</strong> — placeholders are recognizable;
        repeated projection does not re-archive; rewrite / failure / tokens saved are observable.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="observe"
    label="§02 · Observability"
    title="Observability: why the request got smaller"
    lede="Diagnostics explain the shrink; they do not replace correctness tests."
  >
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Active prune diagnostics">activePrunedToolResults
activeArchiveFailures
activeEstimatedTokensSaved</pre>
    <p>
      Purpose: explain why a request got smaller and whether recovery paths were lost along the way.
      Cache hit/miss / request-shape attribution belongs to the later cache teaching ticket (map #34 ·
      #38) — do not confuse it with prune correctness. Mid-turn capacity / newest-step interaction:
      <a href={`${localePath("en", "history/pr/1077")}`}>maka:pr:1077</a> (advanced aside).
    </p>
  </Section>

  <div slot="outline">
    <ul class="outline-list">
      <li>
        Protocol depth: four-reps table · ToolRuntime · archive diamond · Active vs Stale · failure
        matrix · seven invariants
      </li>
      <li>
        Mechanism asides
        <a href={`${localePath("en", "history/pr/316")}`}>maka:pr:316</a> /
        <a href={`${localePath("en", "history/pr/319")}`}>maka:pr:319</a>
        (docs-land 769 secondary)
      </li>
      <li>Current building blocks taught; Target TurnEvidence envelope explicitly not fully landed</li>
      <li>
        Structure hard gates remain necessary; depth = can the reader restate fail-open — not “checklist
        green = depth done”
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</ChapterShell>

